definition.value: An alanine derivative that is the N-phenylacetyl derivative of methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)alaninate
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by citrate.
A methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-(phenylacetyl)alaninate that is the more active R-enantiomer of benalaxyl.
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP).
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by gum arabic.
A methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-(phenylacetyl)alaninate that is the less active S-enantiomer of benalaxyl.
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by 8 nm thick polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP).
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by 38 nm thick polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP).
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by 5 nm thick gum arabic.
Any coated Ag nanoparticle in which the the silver nanoparticles are encapsulated by 22 nm thick gum arabic.
An alanine derivative that is the N-furoyl derivative of methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)alaninate
A methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-2-furoylalaninate that has R configuration.
A methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-2-furoylalaninate that has S configuration.

An alanine derivative that is methyl alaninate in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a methoxyacetyl group, while the other is substituted by a 2,6-dimethylphenyl group.
A methyl N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-(methoxyacetyl)alaninate that is the less active S-enantiomer of metalaxyl.
An aromatic amide that is 2,6-dimethylaniline in which the two amino hydrogens are replaced by chloroacetyl and 2-oxotetrahydrofuran-3-yl groups
A 2-chloro-N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-(2-oxotetrahydrofuran-3-yl)acetamide that is the R-enantiomer of ofurace.
A 2-chloro-N-(2,6-dimethylphenyl)-N-(2-oxotetrahydrofuran-3-yl)acetamide that is the S-enantiomer of ofurace.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from gamma-methyl glutamate.
A fourteen-membered macrocyclic diterpene consisting of 12-isopropylidene-1,5,9-trimethylcyclotetradecane having three endocyclic double bonds located at positions 1, 5 and 9.
A cembrane diterpenoid obtained by regio- and stereoselective hydration of the exocyclic double bond of cembrene C.
A fourteen-membered macrocyclic diterpene consisting of 1,5,9-trimethyl-12-(prop-1-en-2-yl)cyclotetradecane having three endocyclic double bonds located at positions 1, 5 and 9.
A fifteen-membered macrocyclic diterpenoid consisting of (1S,4E,8E,12E)-cyclopentadeca-4,8,12-trien-1-ol carrying five additional methyl substituents at positions 2, 2, 5, 9 and 13.

A subclass of opines, which are low molecular weight compounds found in plant crown gall tumours or hairy root tumours produced by parasitic bacteria of the genus Agrobacterium. Agrocinopines are set of sugar phosphodiester opines known to induce transfer of another Ti plasmid, pTiBo542.

A large family of low molecular weight compounds most commonly found in plant crown gall tumours or hairy root tumours produced by parasitic bacteria of the genus Agrobacterium. They are also found in marine invertebrates, fungi, higher plants and mammals.
A member of the class of agrocinopines that consists of sucrose and L-arabinose units joined via a  phosphodiester linkage between position 4(F) of sucrose and position 2 of arabinose.
A member of the class of agrocinopines that consists of beta-D-fructose and L-arabinose units joined via a phosphodiester linkage between position 4 of fructose and position 2 of arabinose.
A member of the class of agrocinopines that consists of sucrose and D-glucose units joined via a phosphodiester linkage between position 4(F) of sucrose and position 2 of glucose.
A member of the class of agrocinopines that consists of two D-glucose units joined via a (2<->2)-phosphodiester linkage.
A nucleotide conjugate that is produced by Agrobacterium radiobacter strain K-84. A 'Trojan horse' antibiotic used to control crown gall.
An N-acylhexadecasphinganine in which the acyl group is specified as palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl).
An N-acylhexadecasphinganine in which the acyl group is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the nitrogen of the dimethylaminoethyl substituent of diltiazem. The major species at pH 7.3.
A 5-[2-(dimethylamino)ethyl]-2-(4-methoxyphenyl)-4-oxo-2,3,4,5-tetrahydro-1,5-benzothiazepin-3-yl acetate in which both stereocentres have R configuration. It is a cGMP-activated K+ channel blocker.

A lactam that is 2,3-dihydro-1,5-benzothiazepin-4(5H)-one in which positions 2 and 3 are substituted by 4-methoxyphenyl and acetoxy, respectively, while the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 2-(dimethylamino)ethyl group.
An acyl-CoA(4-) oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-(methylthio)propanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the nitrogen of the dimethylaminoethyl substituent of ent-diltiazem. The major species at pH 7.3.
A hydrochloride salt resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of ent-diltiazem and hydrogen chloride.

A dipeptide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-benzyloxycarbonyl-L-valine with the amino group of L-phenylalanine aldehyde. It is a potent cell-permeable inhibitor of calpain I and II, and is also a gamma-secretase inhibitor.
A family of sphingolipids that share a common structural feature, a hexadecasphingosine base backbone.
A family of sphingolipids that share a common structural feature, a hexadecasphinganine base backbone.
A calpain inhibitor that interferes with the action of calpain-2 (EC 3.4.22.53).
A triterpene glycoside obtained from the New Zealand and South Australian sea cucumber Australostichopus mollis.
An EC 3.4.22.* (cysteine endopeptidase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of calpain-3 (EC 3.4.22.54).
An EC 3.4.22.* (cysteine endopeptidase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any calpain.
A triterpene glycoside obtained from the New Zealand and South Australian sea cucumber Australostichopus mollis.
An organic heterotricyclic compound whose skeleton contains a naphthalene fused with a dithiin.
